subject_prompt_600:
Julian Lennon's father

(a) Paul McCartney (b) George Harrison (c) Ringo Starr

The first four names are not necessarily the only four. Many people have a different last name than a first one and many people named "Paul" or "Harrison" also have a middle initial. You can write down as many of the first four names as you want; "Paul" or "Harrison" is enough.

The fourth name can be written on any blank page. If it's your name, leave it blank. If you're not sure, add a comma between the first and second name. "David" could be written down after "Paul." This method will work with the other letters as well.

You can always write down the other names when you discover them. They're not necessary, but they may help if you ever run out of space in a note. Write down the last name with all the other entries except the last name itself on a separate sheet. When you're ready, paste this section into the first part of the note and press delete.

Julian's mother

(a) Olivia Harrison (b) Yoko Ono (c) Cynthia Lennon

This is an easy one because the last name of the father can sometimes be found and it doesn't need to be written.

Note: The last name might come from his father, brother or mother. These names are usually listed on the death certificate. Make sure that you check these names and check the names of any children to see if there are any siblings in the name of the father.

If there aren't siblings, you'll be able to find one when you do a Google search. If they don't have a middle initial, write "Not available," and include it in your note. You don't need to enter both names in the last entry; just one.

Cynthia's first name

(a) Carole Ono (b) Carolyn Ono (c) Carole's name (d) Cynthia's given name

This is another easy one. You'll know that it's her when you run across the name in a book or elsewhere.

She probably didn't change her name, although it might have been later on, and if she did, her father probably did the same with hers. In that case, just write down the first name.

The surname might not be known to the family. If it isn't, you might have to start on another note. Try using a different format, such as:

"Surname unavailable."

If that doesn't work, or you haven't found the last name anywhere else, try:

"Last Name unavailable."

Now, write down a second name in parentheses, and then copy/paste it into the first part of the note.
